Part 3: GKE Multi-Tenancy Security Design 
Estimated 15 minutes 
Scenario 
Your company needs to support multiple development teams deploying to a shared GKE cluster while maintaining strong isolation. Requirements: 
● Five (5) teams (team-alpha, team-beta, team-gamma, team-delta, team-epsilon) ● Each team has different GCP resource access needs 
● Teams should NOT be able to see/access other teams' workloads 
● Each team needs their own Cloud SQL instance, Cloud Storage buckets, and Secret Manager secrets 
● Platform team needs cluster-wide visibility and management 
● Must pass SOC 2 audit requirements for tenant isolation 
Current Cluster State: 
● GKE cluster: `shared-prod-cluster` (GKE Standard, not Autopilot) 
● All teams currently deploying to `default` namespace 
● All pods running with cluster's default service account 
● No network policies configured 
● No resource quotas set 
Your Tasks 
1. Design the namespace and RBAC strategy: 
● How many namespaces? What naming convention? 
● What Kubernetes RBAC roles for each team? 
● What GCP IAM roles for each team's service accounts? 
● How do you prevent namespace-level privilege escalation? 
2. Write Kubernetes YAML configurations for team-alpha including: ● Namespace with proper labels/annotations 
● ServiceAccount with Workload Identity binding 
● Role and RoleBinding for team developers 
● ResourceQuota (CPU, memory, pods) 
● NetworkPolicy for team isolation 
● PodSecurityStandard enforcement 
3. Write the gcloud commands to: 
● Create GCP service account for team-alpha 
● Bind GCP service account to Kubernetes service account (Workload Identity) ● Grant team-alpha's GCP SA access to only their Cloud SQL instance ● Configure Binary Authorization policy for team-alpha's namespace 
4. Describe three (3) ways a malicious insider could break out of this isolation? How would you defend against each?
